com.ibm.xmi.framework
Class XMIContainer

java.lang.Object
  |
  +--com.ibm.xmi.framework.XMIContainer
public class XMIContainer
extends java.lang.Object

This class holds XMI objects. It has three main functions:

  1. Supports getting an object with a given uuid.
  2. Supports getting objects and values with a given XMI name.
  3. Supports getting all objects in the container, not just the top-level ones
  4. Prints objects

Printing objects using an XMIContainer results in printing all of the objects values and all contained objects. Printing objects using the toString() method of the XMIObjectImpl class results in only the id, uuid, label, and owner being printed.

The framework currently does not support sophisticated queries; it is up to you to put your objects, classes, etc. in your own data structures if you need to do more than the simple queries supported by this class.

The Model class acts as a container for classes and packages; see the Model class documentation for more details.

getData

public java.util.Collection getData(java.lang.String name)
Returns all objects and values with the given XMI name. If there are none, it return an empty collection; otherwise, return an unmodifiable collection of XMI objects and values.
Parameters:
name - The XMI name
Returns:
An empty collection or an unmodifiable collection of XMI objects, properties, and links whose XMI names match the given name.

getObjects

public java.util.Collection getObjects()
This method lets you get all objects in the container, not just the top level ones. It returns the top level objects, all contained objects, and all objects that are values of attributes.
Returns:
An empty collection or an unmodifiable collection of all XMI objects in the container, included contained XMI objects and XMI objects that are the values of attributes.

getTopObjects

public java.util.Collection getTopObjects()
This method returns the top level objects in the container; if there are none, it returns an empty collection. Otherwise, it returns an unmodifiable collection of the top level XMI objects.
Returns:
An empty collection or an unmodifiable collection of top level XMI objects (objects not contained in other XMI objects)
